<h4 id="2-architecture">2. Architecture</h4>
<p>math can be divided into four parts, structure, space, change, application, and
discrete.
<img src="/images/math.png" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>Difference between space and structure</li>
</ol>

<ul>
  <li>\(R^N\), Banach space, Normed vector space, Metric space, Hilbert space,
 Inner product space, vector space. modern mathematics uses many types of
 spaces.  it does not define the notion of ‚Äúspace‚Äù itself</li>
  <li>Neither of these words space and structure have a single mathematical
 definition. The English words can be used in essentially all the same
 situations, but you often think of a ‚Äúspace‚Äù as more geometric and a
 ‚Äústructure as more algebraic. So you could thinke of ‚Äústructures‚Äù as places
 we do algebra, and ‚Äúspaces‚Äù we do geometry.</li>
  <li>The distinction between geometric ‚Äúspace‚Äù and algebraic ‚Äústructure‚Äù is
 sometimes clear, sometimes elusive. Clearly, groups are algebraic, while
 Euclidean spaces are geometric.</li>
</ul>

